===Etymology===
Old English ''hel'', ''helle'' (nether world, abode of the dead) < Proto-Germanic ''*khaljo'' (nether world, concealed place) < Proto-Indo-European '''*kel-''' (to cover, conceal, save).

===Noun===
'''hell'''

# In various religions, the place where [[sinner]]s are said to go after death.
# A place of great suffering in life.
# Name of a [[town]] in several locations.
# A place for [[gambling]].
#: ''... the air of moral nihilism common to keepers of gambling hells and disorderly houses'' — [[w:Joseph Conrad|Joseph Conrad]]

===Interjection===
'''hell'''

# Used to express negative discontentment.

